"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767630","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-10-17","<p>The Ministry of Justice does not hold this data. Offences involving domestic abuse can take various forms and are prosecuted under the offence in law that best reflects their nature and circumstances, for example, harassment, assault occasioning actual bodily harm, a public order offence. These offences can take the form of domestic abuse or non-domestic abuse and data collected from courts does not distinguish between the two.</p>","Bracknell","Dr Phillip Lee",,"2017-10-17T16:30:23.9Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767630/answer","Biography information for Dr Phillip Lee","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767630/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767630/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-10-09","Domestic Abuse: Convictions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many people convicted of domestic violence have convictions for violence against (a) two, (b) three and (c) more than three victims.","false","Biography information for Liz Saville Roberts","Dwyfor Meirionnydd","Liz Saville Roberts","106627"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767631","House of Commons Commission","false","2017-10-12","<p>The Parliamentary Estate provides users with a number of different broadband solutions with varying bandwidth based on usage and capacity requirements. These are listed below:</p><ul><li>Parliament’s main secure private network (PN) resilient internet connection = 2Gbps bandwidth</li><li>The secure ‘internet direct’ resilient wireless service = 400Mbps bandwidth</li><li>Broadband over a phone line = 5–7Mbps bandwidth</li></ul><p><br>The Digital Service takes action where possible to improve the broadband download speed across the Parliamentary Estate. However, due to the age and condition of the Palace of Westminster it is difficult to improve both the wiring that is available and to supplement the wireless connectivity.</p><p>The average download speeds on these services will vary as it depends on a number of factors such as the capability of the user’s device, the connection type (wired/wireless), the size of download, the current bandwidth utilisation on any given day and the volume of users/devices connected, as these internet services and bandwidths are shared with all users across the Parliamentary estate. Due to these factors, the Digital Service does not hold data relating to the average download speed.</p>","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake",,"2017-10-12T13:02:06.14Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767631/answer","Biography information for Tom Brake","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767631/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767631/answer",,,,,"18","House of Commons Commission","House of Commons Commission","2017-10-09","Parliament: Broadband","1","House of Commons","To ask the right hon. Member for Carshalton and Wallington, representing the House of Commons Commission, what the average broadband download speed is on the Parliamentary estate.","false","Biography information for Tom Watson","West Bromwich East","Tom Watson","106531"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767632","Department for International Development","false","2017-10-18","<p>The UK will provide £1.9 million to the United Nations Children’s Fund (UNICEF) in Gaza to address critical water, sanitation and hygiene needs, benefitting approximately 1 million people. UNICEF performs a unique role in supporting vulnerable people in the most complex settings and is committed to taking forwards the UK’s ambitious UN reform agenda.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2017-10-18T12:10:41.457Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767632/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767632/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767632/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-10-09","Gaza: Humanitarian Aid","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, whether her Department has responded to the appeal from humanitarian agencies for a global fund of $25 million for humanitarian funding for life-saving interventions in the Gaza Strip.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","106501"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767633","Department for International Development","false","2017-10-12","<p>The Secretary of State has concluded a full examination of DFID’s programme in the Occupied Palestinian Territories (OPTs). The outcomes of the examination are reflected in DFID’s published country profile for the Occupied Palestinian Territories which can be found online at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/dfid-occupied-palestinian-territories-profile-july-2017" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/dfid-occupied-palestinian-territories-profile-july-2017</a>.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2017-10-12T12:03:54.937Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767633/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767633/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767633/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-10-09","Occupied Territories: Overseas Aid","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, when she plans to publish the review of her Department's aid programme in the Occupied Palestinian Territories.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","106502"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767634","Department for International Development","false","2017-10-16","<p>Data for all DFID’s spend is available on the Statistics for International Development (SID) website at</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/statistics-on-international-development" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/statistics-on-international-development</a>. SID does not differentiate between DFID’s spend in the West Bank and Gaza.</p><p>The UK provided more than £17 million in immediate humanitarian assistance for those affected by the Gaza conflict in the summer of 2014. In October 2014, the UK pledged a further £20 million in early recovery assistance at the Gaza Reconstruction Conference in Cairo, including support for cash assistance to Palestinian refugees, mine removal and medical treatment. The UK has disbursed this pledge in its entirety. Since then the UK has provided additional support to Gaza, including supporting basic service delivery, such as health and education, through the United Nations Relief and Works Agency for Palestine Refugees (UNRWA), supporting humanitarian access, enabling reconstruction efforts and investing in job creation.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2017-10-16T17:03:25.767Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767634/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767634/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767634/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-10-09","Gaza: Overseas Aid","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, how much aid the Government provided to Gaza in financial year (a) 2013-14, (b) 2014-15, (c) 2015-16 and (d) 2016-17; and what proportion of the sum her Department plans to provide to the Occupied Palestinian Territories for financial year 2017-18 will be used to support the people of Gaza.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","106488"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767635","Department for International Development","false","2017-10-16","<p>Through the Palestinian Market Development Programme (PMDP) DFID has supported 264 businesses in Gaza to recover from the 2014 Gaza war. As a result of electricity shortages some PMDP beneficiaries have had to cease operations and others have responded by taking actions such as adjusting working hours, operating below capacity and using more expensive sources of electricity such as generators. We urge all the parties to find a sustainable solution to increase electricity supply.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2017-10-16T17:04:03.95Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767635/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767635/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767635/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-10-09","Gaza: Overseas Aid","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what effect the electricity crisis has had on recipients of support from the UK's Palestinian Market Development Programme in Gaza; and whether those recipients have experienced a decrease in the viability and productivity of their businesses due to that crisis.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","106489"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767636","Department for International Development","false","2017-10-16","<p>According to the Food Security Sector (FSS) in the Occupied Palestinian Territories (OPTs), direct damages to agricultural produce as a result of electricity shortages are estimated at approximately 78,000 tons of vegetables, equivalent to 78 million New Israeli Shekels (£16.25 million) of lost revenues to agricultural workers. The UN Office for the Coordination of Humanitarian Affairs has indicated that electricity shortages are creating increasingly unsustainable conditions for most of the agricultural production sector with significant loss of revenues for agricultural workers.</p><p> </p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2017-10-16T17:01:10.693Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767636/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767636/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767636/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-10-09","Gaza: Electricity","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what assessment she has made of the (a) effect of the ongoing electricity crisis on food security in the Gaza Strip and (b) long-term implications of the electricity crisis of agricultural production in the Gaza Strip.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","106490"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767637","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-10-12","<p>The UK has not provided any funding or combat training to the Burmese military, although we have been providing education training. In addition to English language training the Ministry of Defence has provided courses covering governance, human rights, accountability and international law. These courses were delivered by the Defence Academy in Burma and here in the UK.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2017-10-12T15:07:57.597Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767637/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767637/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767637/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-10-09","Burma: Military Aid","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, whether the UK has provided funding, training or other support to the military forces of Myanmar in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","106685"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767638","Department for International Development","false","2017-10-16","<p>The Department for International Development has not allocated any funds to supporting engagement with Iran on economic development and openness.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2017-10-16T17:05:37.613Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767638/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767638/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767638/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-10-09","Iran: Overseas Aid","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, pursuant to the oral contribution by the Minister for the Middle East on 18 July 2017, Official Report, column 297WH, what funds her Department has allocated to supporting engagement with Iran on economic development and openness.","false","Biography information for Tulip Siddiq","Hampstead and Kilburn","Tulip Siddiq","106660"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767639","Department for International Development","false","2017-10-16","<p>The Department for International Development (DFID) has not provided any funding to Iran to assist with human rights projects since 2010, and has no plans to do so in future. Between 2011 and 2015, the UK held no diplomatic relations with Iran.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2017-10-16T17:05:06.617Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767639/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767639/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767639/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-10-09","Iran: Overseas Aid","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, how much funding her Department has provided to Iran to assist with human rights projects in each year since 2010-11; and how much such funding she plans to allocate in future years.","false","Biography information for Tulip Siddiq","Hampstead and Kilburn","Tulip Siddiq","106595"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767640","Department for International Development","false","2017-10-16","<p>Exit is an all-of-government operation. The Department for Exiting the European Union is doing detailed work with departments to prepare for the upcoming negotiations by understanding the risks and opportunities of leaving the EU and coordinating planning.</p><p>Staff within the DFID Europe Department and DFID Trade for Development team based in the Department for International Trade, lead on providing advice to Ministers on EU Exit and exit-related issues and projects.</p><p>Members of staff across the Department also provide advice and analysis on EU Exit issues as required.</p><p>Given the interactions between EU Exit work and the Department’s other priorities, it would not be possible to give an accurate figure.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2017-10-16T07:49:18.557Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767640/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767640/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767640/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-10-09","Department for International Development: Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what estimate her Department has made of the proportion of the Civil Service workforce in her Department dedicated to planning for (a) the UK leaving the EU and (b) projects relating to the UK leaving the EU.","false","Biography information for Mr David Lammy","Tottenham","Mr David Lammy","106578"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767641","Department for International Development","false","2017-10-17","<p>We remain concerned about the situation in Gaza and continue to monitor it closely. The UK’s Ambassador in Tel Aviv and our Consul-General in Jerusalem have raised our concerns with the Israeli authorities and the Palestinian Authority (PA) respectively. We have encouraged the PA to ensure their policy in Gaza does not unnecessarily impact the civilian population. We urge all the parties to find a sustainable solution. The UK is a long-term supporter of United Nations Relief and Works Agency for Palestine Refugees (UNRWA) which provides basic services to 1.3 million people in Gaza including basic health care, and we are supporting humanitarian access, enabling reconstruction efforts and investing in job creation.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2017-10-17T08:09:29.453Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767641/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767641/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767641/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-10-09","Gaza: Electricity","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what steps her Department is taking to provide funding and support to people in Gaza to restore full electricity supply from domestic and international sources.","false","Biography information for Julie Cooper","Burnley","Julie Cooper","106805"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767642","Department for International Development","false","2017-10-18","<p>The UK will provide £1.9 million to the United Nations Children’s Fund (UNICEF) in Gaza to address critical water, sanitation and hygiene needs, benefitting approximately 1 million people. UNICEF performs a unique role in supporting vulnerable people in the most complex settings and is committed to taking forwards the UK’s ambitious UN reform agenda.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2017-10-18T12:12:29.267Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767642/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767642/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767642/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-10-09","Gaza: Humanitarian Aid","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what steps her Department is taking to support the UN Office for the Coordination of Humanitarian Affairs humanitarian funding appeal to support people in Gaza.","false","Biography information for Julie Cooper","Burnley","Julie Cooper","106806"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767643","Department for International Development","false","2017-10-17","<p>We remain concerned about the humanitarian situation in Gaza and continue to monitor it closely, including the effect electricity shortages are having on the health sector. We urge all the parties to find a sustainable solution. The UK is a long-term supporter of United Nations Relief and Works Agency for Palestine Refugees (UNRWA) which provides basic services to 1.3 million people in Gaza including basic health care.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2017-10-17T08:08:41.01Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767643/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767643/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767643/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-10-09","Gaza: Health Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what steps her Department is taking to provide funding and support to healthcare centres in Gaza which are operating without electricity or fuel for backup generators.","false","Biography information for Julie Cooper","Burnley","Julie Cooper","106727"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767644","Department for International Development","false","2017-10-16","<p>Urgent improvements to infrastructure in Gaza are essential to improve living conditions. DFID has provided technical assistance for feasibility studies for the Gaza desalinisation plant which will improve water security, and has supported the development of Gazan irrigation systems through the rehabilitation of water infrastructure. The UK is a shareholder in a number of major international financial institutions, such as the International Bank for Reconstruction and Development and the European Investment Bank, which support infrastructure projects across the Occupied Palestinian Territories (OPTs). The UK regularly raises the issue of water in the OPTs with the Israeli authorities to ensure fair distribution of water across the OPTs.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2017-10-16T15:10:43.473Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767644/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767644/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767644/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-10-09","Gaza: Sanitation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what steps her Department is taking to provide funding and support to improve the ageing water and sanitation infrastructure of the Gaza strip.","false","Biography information for Julie Cooper","Burnley","Julie Cooper","106728"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767645","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-10-18","<p>Twenty defendants were proceeded against at magistrates’ courts for offences under Breeding and Sale of Dogs Act from 2012 to 2016. Of these, one defendant is listed as being a pet shop.</p><p>Twenty-four defendants were proceeded against for offences related to failing to comply with the conditions of a pet shop licence.</p><p>These figures relate to persons for whom these offences were the principal offences for which they were dealt with. When a defendant has been found guilty of two or more offences it is the offence for which the heaviest penalty is imposed. Where the same penalty is imposed for two or more offences, the offence selected is the offence for which the statutory maximum penalty is the most severe.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2017-10-18T16:32:27.013Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767645/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767645/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767645/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-10-09","Animal Welfare: Prosecutions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, how many investigations into unlicensed (a) dog breeding and (b) pet shops have led to a prosecution in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Chris Evans","Islwyn","Chris Evans","106738"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767646","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-10-17","<p>‘<strong>Help with Prison Visits’</strong> is a new digital service, launched in June 2017, that administers the Assisted Prison Visits Scheme in addition to the paper process. It has been essential to develop an alternative payment method for our most vulnerable claimants as giro cheques have been discontinued.</p><p>We have been monitoring and improving the service since it was launched and plan to evaluate implementation more fully in the New Year.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2017-10-17T16:39:25.853Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767646/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767646/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767646/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-10-09","Prisons: Visits","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what assessment he has made of the effect on assisted prison visits of the system going online.","false","Biography information for Mike Kane","Wythenshawe and Sale East","Mike Kane","106748"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767647","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-10-16","<p>We carried out a comprehensive review of the probation system to examine all aspects of probation delivery since the implementation of the Transforming Rehabilitation reforms. As a result of this review, and as set out in my written statement of 19 July 2017, we amended CRC contracts to reflect more accurately the fixed costs of delivering services to offenders and enable providers to focus on delivery of critical operational services. We continue to keep the operation of the probation system under review and are exploring further improvements that could be made to the delivery of services.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2017-10-16T14:37:43.167Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767647/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767647/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767647/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-10-09","Community Rehabilitation Companies","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, whether the Government's review of community rehabilitation companies in England and Wales has been completed; and what the main conclusions are of that review.","false","Biography information for Liz Saville Roberts","Dwyfor Meirionnydd","Liz Saville Roberts","106608"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767648","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-10-18","<p>The UK's departure from the European Union impacts upon most areas of departmental business. Staff within the Department’s Global Britain Directorate lead on providing advice to Ministers on EU Exit and exit-related issues. However, members of staff across the Department also provide advice and analysis on EU Exit issues as required. Given the interactions between EU exit work and the Department’s other priorities, it would not be possible to give a precise figure.</p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab",,"2017-10-18T14:51:52.68Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767648/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767648/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767648/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-10-09","Ministry of Justice: Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what estimate his Department has made of the proportion of the Civil Service workforce in his Department dedicated to planning for (a) the UK leaving the EU and (b) projects relating to the UK leaving the EU.","false","Biography information for Mr David Lammy","Tottenham","Mr David Lammy","106580"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767649","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-10-17","<p>The Government is committed to introducing legislation to modernise the courts system as soon as parliamentary time allows.</p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab",,"2017-10-17T15:03:42.637Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767649/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767649/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767649/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-10-09","Courts","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, when his Department plans to introduce the Courts Bill.","false","Biography information for Liz Saville Roberts","Dwyfor Meirionnydd","Liz Saville Roberts","106622"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767650","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-10-17","<p>The information requested is not held centrally.</p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab",,"2017-10-17T15:01:34.883Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767650/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767650/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767650/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-10-09","Rape: Trials","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many applications were made by defence lawyers to the Crown Court to cross-examine rape victims on their sexual history in each of the last three years; and on how many occasions those applications were granted.","false","Biography information for Liz Saville Roberts","Dwyfor Meirionnydd","Liz Saville Roberts","106623"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767651","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-10-17","<p>The performance of all Community Rehabilitation Companies is assessed through a range of service levels and through a robust contract management and assurance process. Performance information against these service levels is published quarterly, and the latest data can be found at:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/633101/community-performance-quarterly-mi-jan-mar-2017.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/633101/community-performance-quarterly-mi-jan-mar-2017.pdf</a></p><p> </p><p>Public protection is our top priority and we will take all necessary action to make sure the probation system is reducing reoffending and preventing future victims.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah","106612 ; 106613","2017-10-17T13:55:54.747Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767651/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767651/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767651/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-10-09","London Community Rehabilitation Company","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what recent assessment he has made of the effectiveness and performance of the London Community Rehabilitation Service.","false","Biography information for Liz Saville Roberts","Dwyfor Meirionnydd","Liz Saville Roberts","106614"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767652","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-10-17","<p>The performance of all Community Rehabilitation Companies is assessed through a range of service levels and through a robust contract management and assurance process. Performance information against these service levels is published quarterly, and the latest data can be found at:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/633101/community-performance-quarterly-mi-jan-mar-2017.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/633101/community-performance-quarterly-mi-jan-mar-2017.pdf</a></p><p> </p><p>Public protection is our top priority and we will take all necessary action to make sure the probation system is reducing reoffending and preventing future victims.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah","106612 ; 106614","2017-10-17T13:55:54.7Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767652/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767652/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767652/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-10-09","Wales Community Rehabilitation Company","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what recent assessment he has made of the effectiveness and performance of the Wales Community Rehabilitation Service.","false","Biography information for Liz Saville Roberts","Dwyfor Meirionnydd","Liz Saville Roberts","106613"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767653","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-10-17","<p>We are committed to improving the delivery of local criminal justice services, and are working with a range of stakeholders, including Police and Crime Commissioners, Local Authorities and other government departments, to do this.</p><p> </p><p>We have agreed justice devolution deals with London and combined authorities in Greater Manchester, the Liverpool City region and Cambridgeshire and Peterborough. We have a Memorandum of Understanding in place with Greater Manchester Combined Authority to support collaborative working, and are in discussion with other regions, including London, about further opportunities.</p><p> </p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2017-10-17T13:55:26.287Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767653/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767653/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767653/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-10-09","Probation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, whether he plans to devolve the operation of any probation functions in England and Wales to (a) local authorities or (b) police commissioners.","false","Biography information for Liz Saville Roberts","Dwyfor Meirionnydd","Liz Saville Roberts","106611"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767654","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-10-17","<p>The performance of all Community Rehabilitation Companies is assessed through a range of service levels and through a robust contract management and assurance process. Performance information against these service levels is published quarterly, and the latest data can be found at:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/633101/community-performance-quarterly-mi-jan-mar-2017.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/633101/community-performance-quarterly-mi-jan-mar-2017.pdf</a></p><p> </p><p>Public protection is our top priority and we will take all necessary action to make sure the probation system is reducing reoffending and preventing future victims.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah","106613 ; 106614","2017-10-17T13:55:54.653Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767654/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767654/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767654/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-10-09","Durham Tees Valley Community Rehabilitation Company","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what recent assessment he has made of the effectiveness and performance of the Tees Valley Community Rehabilitation Service.","false","Biography information for Liz Saville Roberts","Dwyfor Meirionnydd","Liz Saville Roberts","106612"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767655","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-10-16","<p>Since the implementation of the Transforming Rehabilitation reforms, the National Probation Service (NPS) and Community Rehabilitation Companies (CRCs) have been monitored against performance frameworks to make sure their services are protecting the public, reducing reoffending and delivering the orders of the court.</p><p>We closely monitor and robustly manage CRCs to make sure they fulfil their contractual commitments. Data on both NPS and CRC performance against service levels is published quarterly, with the latest data published in July: https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/community-performance-quarterly-and-annual-2016-to-2017.</p><p>We acknowledge there have been issues with how probation services are performing and we have taken action, as I set out in my statement in July. We will continue to work with both CRCs and NPS to improve delivery and ensure we provide a service that protects the public and helps rehabilitate offenders.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2017-10-16T14:37:26.47Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767655/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767655/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767655/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-10-09","Probation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what assessment he has made of the effect on performance of the probation reforms introduced in 2013.","false","Biography information for Liz Saville Roberts","Dwyfor Meirionnydd","Liz Saville Roberts","106609"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767656","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-10-16","<p>The successful delivery of probation services relies on the work of public and private sector providers, as well as a range of other organisations including voluntary sector bodies and mutuals.</p><p>The department has contracts with 21 Community Rehabilitation Companies (CRCs). Nineteen of the 21 CRCs are being run with assistance from staff mutuals or voluntary sector organisations.</p><p>We do not currently have plans to expand the role of mutuals in the delivery of probation services. Probation providers will continue to work with a range of partners to ensure they protect the public and rehabilitate offenders.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2017-10-16T14:36:56.39Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767656/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767656/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767656/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-10-09","Probation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, whether he plans to expand the role of mutuals in the management of probation services in England and Wales.","false","Biography information for Liz Saville Roberts","Dwyfor Meirionnydd","Liz Saville Roberts","106610"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767657","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-10-17","<p>Courts regularly handle extremely sensitive cases and have a range of measures in place to maintain the confidentiality of participants’ details including victims of domestic abuse.</p><p>In the Criminal Courts, there is no requirement for a victim’s address to be provided in their written statement, therefore these courts do not need guidance to prevent disclosure.</p><p>The Family Courts follow guidance laid out in Standard Operating Procedures that requires all files with confidential addresses to be checked by a manager or another officer.</p><p>In the civil courts, there is no formal guidance, however where the address of the applicant or respondent is required, victims of domestic abuse are able to apply to have their safe address withheld and provide an alternative address.</p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab",,"2017-10-17T15:02:39.217Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767657/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767657/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767657/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-10-09","Courts: Domestic Abuse","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what guidance prevents the disclosure of the address of a victim of domestic violence to their alleged perpetrator during court proceedings.","false","Biography information for Liz Saville Roberts","Dwyfor Meirionnydd","Liz Saville Roberts","106632"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767658","Ministry of Justice","false","2018-01-22","<p>The Government has no current plan to limit the disclosure of addresses of victims of domestic violence to judges and magistrates in court proceedings.</p><p> </p><p>There are a number of protections already available to parties in the civil and family courts, including measures to protect a ‘safe’ address by providing an alternative. In the criminal courts, victims are not automatically required to disclose their address either on court papers or in the court room.</p>","South East Cambridgeshire","Lucy Frazer",,"2018-01-22T19:48:46.703Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767658/answer","Biography information for Lucy Frazer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767658/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767658/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-10-09","Courts: Domestic Abuse","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, if he will take steps to limit the disclosure of addresses of victims of domestic violence to judges and magistrates in court proceedings.","false","Biography information for Liz Saville Roberts","Dwyfor Meirionnydd","Liz Saville Roberts","106631"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767659","Home Office","false","2017-10-17","<p>Stalking and harassment are devastating crimes which cause great distress to victims. That is why we strengthened the law by creating specific stalking offences in 2012 and raising the maximum sentence for stalking and harassment to 10 years through the Policing and Crime Act 2017.</p><p> </p><p>Support for victims requires more than prosecution after the fact. That is why, we are introducing a new Stalking Protection Order to support victims of stalking at an earlier stage and address the perpetrator’s behaviours before they become entrenched. The new stalking protection order will support existing tools to ensure there are robust protections available to victims of ‘stranger stalking’.</p><p> </p><p>Primary legislation is required to introduce the order and will be taken forward as soon as Parliamentary time allows.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2017-10-17T16:41:00.957Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767659/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767659/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767659/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-10-09","Stalking","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, whether her Department has plans to introduce a stalking protection order.","false","Biography information for Liz Saville Roberts","Dwyfor Meirionnydd","Liz Saville Roberts","106630"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767660","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-10-16","<p>The categories of crime which trigger a SFO review were changed in 2008. The offence of wounding with intent to cause grievous bodily harm was removed from the list of qualifying offences which trigger a mandatory SFO review. There have been no further change to the list of qualifying offences.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2017-10-16T14:36:15.043Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767660/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767660/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767660/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-10-09","Reoffenders","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, whether changes have been made to the list of offences capable of triggering a Serious Further Offence review in respect of an offender under probation at any time during the last 10 years.","false","Biography information for Liz Saville Roberts","Dwyfor Meirionnydd","Liz Saville Roberts","106615"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767661","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-10-16","<p>Her Majesty’s Prison and Probation Service (HMPPS) does not hold information on the average cost of preparing meals in prisons. This could only be provided at a disproportionate cost.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2017-10-16T14:37:05.863Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767661/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767661/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767661/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-10-09","Prisons: Food","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what the average cost is of preparing and serving a meal in prisons.","false","Biography information for Royston Smith","Southampton, Itchen","Royston Smith","106510"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767662","Northern Ireland Office","false","2017-10-16","<p>EU Exit affects a number of work areas across the Department and will therefore encompass a proportion of workload for many staff, the amount of which will vary over time. The Department has recently restructured its approach to the way it handles EU Exit work, moving from a central EU Exit co-ordinating team of 7 to a position in which core EU Exit work is distributed more widely across the whole department.</p><p> </p>","Norwich North","Chloe Smith",,"2017-10-16T10:19:09.383Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767662/answer","Biography information for Chloe Smith","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767662/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767662/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2017-10-09","Northern Ireland Office: Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, what estimate his Department has made of the proportion of the Civil Service workforce in his Department dedicated to planning for (a) the UK leaving the EU and (b) projects relating to the UK leaving the EU.","false","Biography information for Mr David Lammy","Tottenham","Mr David Lammy","106581"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767663","Northern Ireland Office","false","2017-10-16","<p>Ministers in the Northern Ireland Office have had no discussions with the Northern Ireland Assembly on guidance to improve the safety of painkillers as this is a devolved matter.</p><p>We want to see a restored Executive to take forward policy decisions in devolved areas and to provide the political decision making that Northern Ireland needs.</p>","Norwich North","Chloe Smith",,"2017-10-16T10:23:56.417Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767663/answer","Biography information for Chloe Smith","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767663/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767663/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2017-10-09","Analgesics: Northern Ireland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, what discussions he has had with the Northern Ireland Assembly on guidance to improve safety of painkillers.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","106712"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767664","Scotland Office","false","2017-10-17","<p>The UK’s exit from the EU is an all-of-government operation. The Department for Exiting the European Union is doing detailed work with departments to prepare for the upcoming negotiations by understanding the risks and opportunities of leaving the EU and coordinating planning. Staff across the Scotland Office provide advice to Ministers on EU Exit and exit-related issues. Given the interactions between EU exit work and the Department’s other priorities, it would not be possible to give an accurate figure.</p><p> </p>","Dumfriesshire, Clydesdale and Tweeddale","David Mundell",,"2017-10-17T09:09:25.517Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767664/answer","Biography information for David Mundell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767664/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767664/answer",,,,,"2","Scotland","Scotland","2017-10-09","Scotland Office: Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Scotland, what estimate his Department has made of the proportion of the Civil Service workforce in his Department dedicated to planning for (a) the UK leaving the EU and (b) projects relating to the UK leaving the EU.","false","Biography information for Mr David Lammy","Tottenham","Mr David Lammy","106582"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767665","Scotland Office","false","2017-10-17","<p>The membership of the Scottish Business Taskforce, chaired by Lord Dunlop, will be announced in advance of the first meeting which will take place on 27 October.</p>","Dumfriesshire, Clydesdale and Tweeddale","David Mundell",,"2017-10-17T09:10:21.207Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767665/answer","Biography information for David Mundell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767665/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767665/answer",,,,,"2","Scotland","Scotland","2017-10-09","Scottish Business Taskforce","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Scotland, if he will publish the membership of the new Scottish business taskforce he announced on 16 September 2017.","false","Biography information for Stewart Hosie","Dundee East","Stewart Hosie","106477"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767666","Department for Transport","false","2017-10-17","<p>The whole of the Government is preparing for the UK to make an orderly and successful exit from the European Union. The Department for Exiting the European Union is doing detailed work with Departments to prepare for the upcoming negotiations by understanding the risks and opportunities of leaving the EU and coordinating planning. Staff within the International and Regulatory Reform Directorate of the Department for Transport lead on providing advice to Ministers on EU Exit and exit-related issues. Members of staff across this Department also provide advice and analysis on EU Exit issues as required. Given the interactions between EU Exit work and the Department’s other priorities, it is not possible to give an accurate figure.</p><p> </p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2017-10-17T15:06:36.893Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767666/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767666/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767666/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-10-09","Department for Transport: Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what estimate his Department has made of the proportion of the Civil Service workforce in his Department dedicated to planning for (a) the UK leaving the EU and (b) projects relating to the UK leaving the EU.","false","Biography information for Mr David Lammy","Tottenham","Mr David Lammy","106583"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767667","Department for Transport","false","2017-10-12","<p>The Government consulted on proposals for an Independent Commission on Civil Aviation Noise as part of its UK Airspace Policy consultation. We intend to respond to the consultation in the autumn, outlining the Commission’s remit and powers.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2017-10-12T15:15:20.667Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767667/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767667/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767667/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-10-09","Aviation: Noise","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what (a) remit and (b) powers he plans to give the Independent Commission on Civil Aviation Noise.","false","Biography information for Zac Goldsmith","Richmond Park","Zac Goldsmith","106690"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767668","Department for Transport","false","2017-10-12","<p>The process to appoint the lead commissioner for the Independent Commission on Civil aviation noise will be in line with the Code of Practice issued by the Commissioner for Public Appointments.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2017-10-12T15:17:03.02Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767668/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767668/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767668/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-10-09","Aviation: Noise","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what process he plans to put in place to identify and recruit the lead commissioner for the Independent Commission on Civil Aviation Noise.","false","Biography information for Zac Goldsmith","Richmond Park","Zac Goldsmith","106708"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767669","Department for Transport","false","2017-10-12","<p>The Government consulted on proposals for an Independent Commission on Civil Aviation Noise as part of its UK Airspace Policy consultation. We intend to respond to the consultation in the autumn, outlining the timetable for the Commission’s establishment.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2017-10-12T15:16:17.19Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767669/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767669/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767669/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-10-09","Aviation: Noise","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, when he plans to establish the proposed Independent Commission on Civil Aviation Noise.","false","Biography information for Zac Goldsmith","Richmond Park","Zac Goldsmith","106709"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767670","Department for Transport","false","2017-10-17","<p>The International Safety Management (ISM) Code provides an international standard for the safe management and operation of ships. For ships to which the ISM Code applies, the ship’s operator needs to have in place the appropriate procedures for managing all shipboard operations which include the handling of fuel oil (bunkering or cargo transfer) on board a ship and measures to deal with emergency situations, such as an oil spill. The operator must also identify all risks associated with their operations which will include this aspect and instigate appropriate safeguards against the identified risks.</p><p> </p><p>The Maritime and Coastguard Agency audit the ship’s operator’s safety management system periodically to ensure that the company/vessel remains in compliance with the requirements of the ISM Code and take appropriate action where the operator is falling below the required standards.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2017-10-17T13:55:24.307Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767670/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767670/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767670/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-10-09","Shipping: Fuel Oil","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what steps he has taken to improve safety when fuel oil is discharged from maritime vehicles.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","106704"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767671","Department for Transport","false","2017-10-17","<p>We are developing plans to adjust the Overhead Line Equipment between Bedford and London in order to enable the new trains coming into service on the Midland Main Line from 2022 to run at the improved line speeds.</p><p> </p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2017-10-17T14:53:19.257Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767671/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767671/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767671/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-10-09","Railways: Electrification","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what plans his Department has to modify overhead electrification equipment between Bedford and London.","false","Biography information for Mohammad Yasin","Bedford","Mohammad Yasin","106743"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767672","Department for Transport","false","2017-10-17","<p>The upgrade to the Midland Main Line, which includes electrification to Kettering and Corby, will enable increased passenger capacity and reduced journey times, as well as introducing a brand new fleet of bi-mode intercity trains from 2022. This will deliver improved journeys sooner and is part of delivering the biggest upgrade of the Midland Main Line since it opened in 1870. We will only electrify lines where it delivers a genuine benefit to passengers.</p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2017-10-17T15:32:41.023Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767672/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767672/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767672/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-10-09","Midland Main Railway Line: Electrification","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, whether he plans to review the decision to cancel the electrification of the entire Midland Main Line.","false","Biography information for Mohammad Yasin","Bedford","Mohammad Yasin","106744"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767673","Department for Transport","false","2017-10-17","<p>No firm decision on rail services in the next East Midlands franchise has yet been taken. The next franchise starts in August 2019. Invitations to Tender are due to be issued to potential bidders in April 2018. All options for rail services in the next franchise are subject to analysis of the potential benefits and our consultation with stakeholders, which closed on 11 October.</p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard","106745 ; 106772","2017-10-17T13:47:15.523Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767673/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767673/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767673/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-10-09","East Midlands Rail Franchise","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, whether he plans to make it his policy that commuter trains will stop at additional stops between Corby and London St Pancras as a result of the conclusion of the East Midlands Train Consultation.","false","Biography information for Mohammad Yasin","Bedford","Mohammad Yasin","106771"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767674","Department for Transport","false","2017-10-17","<p>Consistent with the <em>Noise Policy Statement for England 2010</em>, the HS2 Programme sets two threshold effect levels for ground-borne noise and vibration, one where adverse effects can be observed (Lowest Observed Adverse Effect Level - LOAELs), and a higher one where significant adverse effects can be observed (Significant Observed Adverse Effect Level - SOAELs). These thresholds are based on the relevant British Standard:<em> ‘</em><em>British Standards Institution (2008), BS6472-1, Guide to Evaluation of Human Exposure to Vibration in Buildings, Part 1: Vibration Sources other than Blasting’.</em></p><p><em> </em></p><p>Further details can be found in the HS2 Phase One Information Paper E21, ‘<em>Control of Ground-Borne Noise and Vibration from the Operation of Temporary and Permanent Railways’</em> at the below link:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/593574/E21_-_Control_of_ground-borne_noise_and_vibration_v1.4.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/593574/E21_-_Control_of_ground-borne_noise_and_vibration_v1.4.pdf</a></p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2017-10-17T15:20:02.663Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767674/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767674/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767674/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-10-09","High Speed Trains: Noise","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, whether any studies or reports have been commissioned by HS2 Ltd or his Department on tolerances of vibration levels on high speed rail.","false","Biography information for Antoinette Sandbach","Eddisbury","Antoinette Sandbach","106720"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767675","Department for Transport","false","2017-10-17","<p>HS2 Ltd is making good progress in implementing Ian Bynoe’s thirteen recommendations and his one suggestion. Of the thirteen recommendations, eleven have been addressed including the publishing of the updated Residents’ Charter in July 2017 and the Community Engagement Strategy in September 2017. There are two remaining recommendations which have already seen improvements and will be fully addressed by the end of December 2017.</p><p> </p><p>Work is in train to implement the report’s suggestion, to establish a best practice advisory panel comprising practitioners who have dealt with comparable community engagement challenges to that of HS2. The terms of reference for the panel will be considered by HS2 Ltd by the end of the year.</p><p> </p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2017-10-17T15:24:07.263Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767675/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767675/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767675/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-10-09","High Speed Two: Complaints","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, which of the 14 recommendations made in the Ian Bynoe report on HS2 Ltd's complaints handling and community engagement of April 2016 have been implemented by HS2 Ltd.","false","Biography information for Antoinette Sandbach","Eddisbury","Antoinette Sandbach","106721"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767676","Department for Transport","false","2017-10-17","<p>No firm decision on rail services in the next East Midlands franchise has yet been taken. The next franchise starts in August 2019. Invitations to Tender are due to be issued to potential bidders in April 2018. All options for rail services in the next franchise are subject to analysis of the potential benefits and our consultation with stakeholders, which closed on 11 October.</p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard","106745 ; 106771","2017-10-17T13:47:15.65Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767676/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767676/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767676/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-10-09","East Midlands Rail Franchise","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what proportion of Intercity trains that stop at Kettering he plans will also stop at (a) Market Harborough, (b) Loughborough, (c) Beeston, (d) East Midlands Parkway and (e) Derby in response to the East Midlands Train Consultation.","false","Biography information for Mohammad Yasin","Bedford","Mohammad Yasin","106772"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767677","Department for Transport","false","2017-10-17","<p>In general terms, the requirements of rail users are at the heart of the UK’s railway and of rail franchising policy.</p><p> </p><p>There is a robust process in place for determining the requirements of rail users, by way of the public consultations process as part of each franchise competition.</p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2017-10-17T14:56:25.343Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767677/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767677/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767677/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-10-09","Railways: Bedford","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what assessment he has made of the adequacy of the overall provision of Thameslink, London Midland and East Midlands services from London to Bedford to determine the requirements of rail users.","false","Biography information for Mohammad Yasin","Bedford","Mohammad Yasin","106773"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767678","Department for Transport","false","2017-10-17","<p>A minimum service pattern for the train services on the East Midlands rail franchise will be published in April 2018, alongside the Invitation to Tender and Stakeholder Briefing Document. It cannot be published before this date, because the analysis of the public consultation response needs to be considered to determine the final minimum service pattern.</p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2017-10-17T15:37:14.953Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767678/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767678/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767678/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-10-09","East Midlands Rail Franchise: Standards","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, if he will publish a minimum service pattern for the East Midlands rail franchise.","false","Biography information for Mohammad Yasin","Bedford","Mohammad Yasin","106774"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767679","Department for Transport","false","2017-10-17","<p>The Government and rail industry are investing in the biggest improvement in rail travel since the Victorian era, including through the Thameslink Programme and the upgrade of the Midland Main Line.</p><p> </p><p>These programmes will improve rail journeys for passengers using the Midland Main Line to travel into London St Pancras:</p><p>o From May 2018, passengers between Bedford and London will benefit from more frequent Thameslink trains, with more seats.</p><p>o The Thameslink programme will also provide improved connections from Bedford to Farringdon for Crossrail as well as London Bridge.</p><p>o Once the electrification to Corby is complete in 2020, passengers at Corby, Kettering, Wellingborough, Bedford, Luton and Luton Airport Parkway will benefit from a new, dedicated service into London St Pancras. The electric trains will be longer, with more seats.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The rail industry is working together to do all we can to improve services for passengers and will to work hard to keep disruption to a minimum.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2017-10-17T14:49:47.51Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767679/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767679/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767679/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-10-09","Railways: Overcrowding","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what plans he has to incentivise train users to use Thameslink services to alleviate over-crowding on all East Midlands services to and from London.","false","Biography information for Mohammad Yasin","Bedford","Mohammad Yasin","106775"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767680","Department for Transport","false","2017-10-17","<p>There are no published statistics on the annual number of passengers travelling on East Midlands train services from Bedford over the past 10 years.</p><p> </p><p>Passenger rail usage statistics for train operators are available on the Office of Rail and Road data portal at the following link: <a href="http://dataportal.orr.gov.uk/browsereports/12" target="_blank">http://dataportal.orr.gov.uk/browsereports/12</a>.</p><p> </p><p>Estimates of Station Usage gives annual totals for all passengers entering and exiting each station on Great Britain’s rail network, and is available on the Office of Rail and Road data portal at the following link:</p><p><a href="http://orr.gov.uk/statistics/published-stats/station-usage-estimates" target="_blank">http://orr.gov.uk/statistics/published-stats/station-usage-estimates</a></p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2017-10-17T15:27:04.863Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767680/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767680/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767680/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-10-09","East Midlands Trains: Passengers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what estimate his Department has made on the number of passengers using East Midlands train service (a) peak-time north-bound, (b) off-peak north-bound, (c) peak-time south-bound and (d) off-peak south-bound from Bedford in each of the last 10 years.","false","Biography information for Mohammad Yasin","Bedford","Mohammad Yasin","106746"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767681","Department for Transport","false","2017-10-17","<p>No firm decision on rail services in the next East Midlands franchise has yet been taken. The next franchise starts in August 2019. Invitations to Tender are due to be issued to potential bidders in April 2018. All options for rail services in the next franchise are subject to analysis of the potential benefits and our consultation with stakeholders, which closed on 11 October.</p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard","106771 ; 106772","2017-10-17T13:47:15.587Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767681/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767681/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767681/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-10-09","East Midlands Rail Franchise","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, if he will make it his policy to stipulate a minimum journey time from Bedford to London after the grant of the East Midlands train franchise.","false","Biography information for Mohammad Yasin","Bedford","Mohammad Yasin","106745"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767682","Department for Transport","false","2017-10-17","<p>The surveys that my honourable Friend refers to show information about people’s properties, and need to be viewed alongside other data to be interpreted correctly. I have asked HS2 Ltd to provide a thorough briefing to my honourable Friend including these surveys.</p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2017-10-17T14:41:31.69Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767682/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767682/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767682/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-10-09","High Speed Two: Surveying","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, pursuant to the oral contribution of the Parliamentary Under-Secretary of State for Transport of 6 September 2017, 154WH, if he will place in the Library copies of the light detection and ranging surveys completed by HS2 Ltd which identify wet rockhead features in Eddisbury constituency.","false","Biography information for Antoinette Sandbach","Eddisbury","Antoinette Sandbach","106762"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767683","Department for Transport","false","2017-10-17","<p>The Secretary of State has met the VW board member responsible for resolving the emissions scandal and pressed him to ensure that any issues reported with consumers’ vehicles after the emissions repair are dealt with and resolved appropriately. We worked hard to secure important improvements to the Trust Building Measure that the company issued in June, to make sure it would support as many affected owners as possible.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2017-10-17T15:41:12.68Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767683/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767683/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767683/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-10-09","Volkswagen","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what discussions he has had with Volkswagen on emissions repairs for owners who are still experiencing problems.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","106794"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767684","Wales Office","false","2017-10-11","<p>The Department for Exiting the European Union has responsibility for overseeing preparations for the withdrawal of the UK from the EU and conducting these withdrawal negotiations in support of the Prime Minister. In doing this it is working very closely with other Government departments, including the Wales Office.</p><p>The Wales Office has refocused its priorities following the United Kingdom’s vote to leave the European Union and work relating to exiting the EU now forms part of the policy portfolio of most staff.</p><p> </p>","Vale of Glamorgan","Alun Cairns",,"2017-10-11T14:23:44.197Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767684/answer","Biography information for Alun Cairns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767684/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767684/answer",,,,,"28","Wales","Wales","2017-10-09","Wales Office: Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Wales, what estimate his Department has made of the proportion of the Civil Service workforce in his Department dedicated to planning for (a) the UK leaving the EU and (b) projects relating to the UK leaving the EU.","false","Biography information for Mr David Lammy","Tottenham","Mr David Lammy","106585"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767685","Women and Equalities","false","2017-10-17","<p>The £5m funding is available for projects across England to celebrate the centenary of the 1918 Representation of the People Act, educate young people about democracy and encourage women to get involved in politics at all levels.</p><p> </p><p>The Government Equalities Office is in the process of agreeing how the Centenary Fund will be allocated. Given the limited time available and the size of the fund, a full public consultation was not feasible. Instead, we chose to consult widely with women’s organisations and non-governmental organisations on how the Government could support projects next year.</p><p> </p><p>As announced in April this year, the first statue of Millicent Fawcett, a leader of the suffrage movement, was erected in Parliament Square and funded from the £5 million Centenary Fund. Government has contributed just over £706,000 towards the statue’s costs.</p><p> </p><p>We are setting up a £1.5million Women’s Suffrage Centenary Grant Scheme specifically to support local and community groups across the regions of England to celebrate the centenary. This grant scheme has two funding streams: the small grants stream has a ceiling of £2,000 to support small local celebratory events. The larger grant stream will cover projects from £2,000 to £125,000 that will principally focus on increasing young people’s understanding and engagement with democracy as well as encouraging women to participate in public life. There will be a grant administrator to oversee the scheme which will be opening soon.‎ I have written to all members of the House to alert them to our plans and will be writing again when the scheme opens.</p><p> </p><p>We are also developing plans for supporting the reach, impact and legacy of existing centenary activities in a number of cities across England that have a strong suffrage history.</p><p> </p><p>The Barnett formula has been applied to this funding in the usual way and it is for the devolved administrations to decide how they choose to mark the centenary.</p>","Guildford","Anne Milton","106442 ; 106443 ; 106444 ; 106461","2017-10-17T11:40:29.92Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767685/answer","Biography information for Anne Milton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767685/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767685/answer",,,,,"31","Women and Equalities","Women and Equalities","2017-10-09","Monuments: Parliament Square","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for Women and Equalities, how much of the £5 million announced in the Spring Budget 2017 to commemorate the centenary of votes for women will be spent on the statue of Millicent Fawcett in Parliament Square.","false","Biography information for Tom Watson","West Bromwich East","Tom Watson","106441"
