"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767748","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-10-18","<p>It is not possible to estimate the proportion of staff time dedicated to EU exit due to the interdependencies and synergies between EU exit and the Department’s other priorities. Teams across the Department are working on delivering a successful EU exit. This includes full-time staff in central coordination teams, and dedicated resource embedded in policy and delivery teams. The Department will continue to ensure there is an appropriate level of resource to deliver its EU exit programme.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-10-18T15:46:58.067Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767748/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767748/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767748/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-10-09","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy: Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what estimate he has made of the proportion of the Civil Service workforce in his Department dedicated to planning for (a) the UK leaving the EU and (b) projects relating to the UK leaving the EU.","false","Biography information for Mr David Lammy","Tottenham","Mr David Lammy","106567"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767749","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-10-16","<p>Currently there are no plans to bring forward legislative proposals to expand the provision of the Consumer Protection Act 1987 to sole traders or small and medium-sized enterprises.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-10-16T14:15:37.633Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767749/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767749/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767749/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-10-09","Consumers: Protection","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, whether he plans to bring forward legislative proposals to expand the provisions of the Consumer Protection Act 1987 which apply to consumers to (a) sole traders and (b) small and medium-sized enterprises.","false","Biography information for Deidre Brock","Edinburgh North and Leith","Deidre  Brock","106589"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767751","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-10-19","<p>The Each Home Counts review was an independent review, led by Dr. Peter Bonfield, which published its report in December 2016. Implementation of Each Home Counts is being led by industry, with the support of Government. All members of the Implementation Board participate on a voluntary basis with no remuneration and are required to declare any conflicts of interest. Where conflicts are identified members are excluded from any decision making process in which they would have an actual or perceived conflict. Ministers have not met with the Implementation Board since December 2016, but Departmental officials are present at meetings as observers.</p><p>The approach taken by the Board has been to encourage constructive stakeholder participation and engage across the sector. A broad range of stakeholders have been involved, including members representative of GasSafe installers.</p><p>One of the main recommendations from the Review was to establish a quality mark for retrofit energy efficiency and renewable energy measures, and for companies operating in this sector.</p><p>It is for industry to propose how the new quality mark framework will be structured and financed. As indicated in the Review it is intended that action build on good practice so reducing bureaucracy and potential duplication and reducing cost for industry and consumers overall.</p><p>The Each Home Counts review recognised that there is already good practice in the sector and many organisations operate to high standards. Where the quality mark requirements are already being met, companies will be able to apply to operate under the quality mark without further improvements. There is no intention from Government to make participation in the proposed Each Home Counts quality mark mandatory for any business or sector. As there is no regulatory requirement, Government does not plan to conduct a dedicated economic impact assessment for Each Home Counts.</p><p> </p>","Devizes","Claire Perry","106662 ; 106663 ; 106664 ; 106665 ; 106666 ; 106668 ; 106669 ; 106670","2017-10-19T16:32:03.67Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767751/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767751/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767751/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-10-09","Natural Gas: Housing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, whether he is taking to steps to ensure that gas-safe registered installers are not required to undertake additional work as a result of the Each Home Counts review.","false","Biography information for Sir Alan Campbell","Tynemouth","Mr Alan Campbell","106667"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767752","Department for International Trade","false","2017-10-17","<p>Exit is an all-of-government operation. The Department for Exiting the European Union is doing detailed work with departments to prepare for the upcoming negotiations by understanding the risks and opportunities of leaving the EU and coordinating planning.</p><p> </p><p>The Department for International Trade was established as a direct result of the referendum decision to leave the EU to secure UK and global prosperity by promoting and financing international trade and investment and championing free trade.</p><p> </p><p>Given the interactions between EU exit work and the Department’s other priorities, it would not be possible to give an accurate figure.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2017-10-17T16:34:18.083Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767752/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767752/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767752/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-10-09","Department for International Trade: Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, what estimate his Department has made of the proportion of the Civil Service workforce in his Department dedicated to planning for (a) the UK leaving the EU and (b) projects relating to the UK leaving the EU.","false","Biography information for Mr David Lammy","Tottenham","Mr David Lammy","106579"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767753","Department for International Trade","false","2017-10-17","<p>The government is committed to seeking continuity in our current trade and investment relationships as we leave the EU. We look forward to working with our friends and allies in the Commonwealth, including Jamaica, to achieve this.</p><p> </p><p>We want to increase not only UK trading links with the Commonwealth but also encourage greater intra–Commonwealth trade and investment. This will be a theme of the upcoming Commonwealth Summit in London. By creating a more vibrant and free trading environment globally, the UK will be much better placed to expand existing trade and investment relations, thereby promoting prosperity, stability and security.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2017-10-17T16:38:59.68Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767753/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767753/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767753/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-10-09","Overseas Trade: Commonwealth","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, what steps he plans to take to facilitate closer and freer trading relationships with Jamaica and other Commonwealth nations when the UK leaves the EU.","true","Biography information for Mr Philip Hollobone","Kettering","Mr Philip Hollobone","106591"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767754","Department for International Trade","false","2017-10-17","<p>There have been no discussions with the Government of Iran in 2017 on a potential new trade agreement.</p>","Wyre Forest","Mark Garnier",,"2017-10-17T17:02:24.403Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767754/answer","Biography information for Mark Garnier","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767754/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767754/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-10-09","Trade Agreements: Iran","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, whether his Department has discussed a potential new trade agreement with the Government of Iran in 2017.","false","Biography information for Tulip Siddiq","Hampstead and Kilburn","Tulip Siddiq","106594"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767755","Department for International Trade","false","2017-10-17","<p>Since the re-opening of the British Embassy in Tehran in August 2015, the Department for International Trade team in Tehran has been working with UK and Iranian businesses and officials to seek out opportunities for bilateral trade.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Current UK exports of goods and services to Iran, 2010 – 2015 can be found in the ONS Pink Book 2016: <a href="https://www.ons.gov.uk/economy/nationalaccounts/balanceofpayments/adhocs/006656balanceofpaymentsannualgeographicaldatatables" target="_blank">https://www.ons.gov.uk/economy/nationalaccounts/balanceofpayments/adhocs/006656balanceofpaymentsannualgeographicaldatatables</a>.</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p>","Wyre Forest","Mark Garnier",,"2017-10-17T16:56:22.913Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767755/answer","Biography information for Mark Garnier","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767755/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767755/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-10-09","Bilateral Aid: Iran","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, how much bilateral assistance his Department has provided to the Iranian Government in each year since 2010-11.","false","Biography information for Tulip Siddiq","Hampstead and Kilburn","Tulip Siddiq","106648"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767756","Department for International Trade","false","2017-10-17","<p>The government is committed to seeking continuity in its current trade and investment relationships, including those covered by EU Free Trade Agreements or other EU preferential arrangements.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2017-10-17T16:35:47.3Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767756/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767756/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767756/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-10-09","European Free Trade Association","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, what discussions have been had with the EFTA states on the UK continuing with such an agreement after the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Keith Vaz","Leicester East","Keith Vaz","106747"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767757","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2017-10-17","<p>When the UK leaves the European Union, we will also the leave the EU Customs Union and develop and independent trade policy which benefits the whole country.</p><p>The Government is committed to negotiating a deep and special partnership with the European Union and is conducting a wide-ranging programme of analysis. It would not be appropriate, however, to publish details that could undermine the UK's negotiating position with the EU, and Parliament has voted not to publish such details.</p><p> </p>","Wycombe","Mr Steve Baker",,"2017-10-17T14:38:14.33Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767757/answer","Biography information for Mr Steve Baker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767757/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767757/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2017-10-09","Disadvantaged","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, what assessment his Department has made of the effect of leaving the single market and customs union on disadvantaged communities and people working in low-income and insecure jobs.","false","Biography information for Mr David Lammy","Tottenham","Mr David Lammy","106763"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767758","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-11-01","<p>The latest information we have from the Royal Borough of Kensington and Chelsea Council shows that there is a total of 202 households from Grenfell Tower and Walk that need rehousing. To date 61 households have accepted permanent accommodation and 54 households have accepted temporary accommodation.</p><p>The Royal Borough of Kensington and Chelsea Council is working urgently to move all families affected by the Grenfell tragedy into temporary or settled accommodation at the earliest opportunity., The Department for Communities and local government is working to support the Council in achieving this.</p><p>For each family, we will respect their wishes and give them the time and space to make this transition at their own pace, and in a way that best supports them to recover from this tragedy.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-11-01T16:28:26.39Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767758/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767758/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767758/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-10-09","Grenfell Tower: Fires","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, how many children who previously lived in Grenfell Tower are living in hotel accommodation as of 9 October 2017.","false","Biography information for Mr David Lammy","Tottenham","Mr David Lammy","106692"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767759","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2017-10-17","<p>HMRC and Border Force are responsible for the UK’s customs arrangements.</p><p>HMRC are considering the capacity and capability requirements for future customs arrangements as part of their EU exit planning. This will be kept under review as negotiations progress.</p><p>The future customs controls required following EU Exit will depend on the outcome of the negotiations. All options are being considered. In the unlikely event that an agreement with the EU is not reached, the Government will work to ensure that trade between the UK and the EU is as frictionless as possible.</p><p> </p>","Wycombe","Mr Steve Baker",,"2017-10-17T14:38:19.583Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767759/answer","Biography information for Mr Steve Baker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767759/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767759/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2017-10-09","Customs Officers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, what steps his Department is taking to (a) employ and train customs officials and (b) establish customs control posts and additional capacity in the event that the UK leaves the EU without a deal.","false","Biography information for Mr David Lammy","Tottenham","Mr David Lammy","106693"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767760","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2017-10-17","<p>Individual governmental departments are responsible for resourcing and accommodation decisions for all existing and any potential new Arms Length Bodies that fall within their remit. This includes those with regulatory functions. The Government will continue to plan for a range of scenarios and will be ready to take any necessary steps to ensure that we are ready for exit day.</p>","Wycombe","Mr Steve Baker",,"2017-10-17T15:21:41.147Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767760/answer","Biography information for Mr Steve Baker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767760/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767760/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2017-10-09","Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, what steps he has taken to (a) employ and train staff and (b) acquire appropriate premises for a new cadre of regulators in the event that the UK leaves the EU without a deal.","false","Biography information for Mr David Lammy","Tottenham","Mr David Lammy","106694"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767761","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-11-01","<p>DCLG is working closely with the Royal Borough of Kensington and Chelsea to support them in ensuring that residents of Grenfell Tower and Grenfell Walk will be provided with a new home in social housing within the period of one year. London local authorities and housing associations have been proactive in offering accommodation and help to assist. However, it is important to get this right and ensure survivors have choice over their housing options.</p><p>Data we have received from the Council, as of 30 October 2017, show that, of the households that previously lived in Grenfell Tower and Grenfell Walk:</p><ol><li><p>26 were living in permanent accommodation;</p></li><li><p>47 were living in temporary accommodation; and</p></li><li><p>130 were living in emergency accommodation.</p></li></ol>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-11-01T17:44:44.687Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767761/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767761/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767761/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-10-09","Grenfell Tower: Fires","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, how many households that previously lived in Grenfell Tower are living in (a) permanent new homes, (b) temporary accommodation or (c) hotels as of 9 October 2017.","false","Biography information for Mr David Lammy","Tottenham","Mr David Lammy","106700"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767762","Department for Exiting the European Union ","false","2017-10-12","<p>The Business Advisory Council is an important part of our preparations for leaving the EU - allowing us to seek the views of experienced business leaders and to share with them the Government’s vision for a successful Brexit.</p><p>The Council has a rotating membership. Attendees at October’s Council were:</p><ul><li><p>Balfour Beatty</p></li><li><p>WPP</p></li><li><p>HSBC</p></li><li><p>GSK</p></li><li><p>Morgan Stanley</p></li><li><p>Bridgewater</p></li><li><p>JCB</p></li><li><p>Vodafone</p></li><li><p>EY</p></li><li><p>Aston Martin</p></li><li><p>Whitbread</p></li><li><p>Nestle</p></li><li><p>ABF</p></li></ul><p> </p>","Wycombe","Mr Steve Baker",,"2017-10-12T08:33:55.263Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767762/answer","Biography information for Mr Steve Baker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767762/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767762/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union ","Exiting the European Union ","2017-10-09","Business Advisory Council","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, what the membership is of the new Business Council for Brexit.","false","Biography information for Hilary Benn","Leeds Central","Hilary Benn","106785"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767763","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2017-10-24","<p>As the Prime Minister has set out, we want to ensure that families who have built their lives together in the EU and UK are able to stay together. The Government’s policy paper “Safeguarding the position of EU citizens in the UK and UK nationals in the EU” sets out how it proposes to safeguard the position of EU citizens and their family members who are currently living in the UK under the Free Movement Directive (2004/38/EC) once we leave the EU.</p>","Worcester","Mr Robin Walker",,"2017-10-24T13:55:10.63Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767763/answer","Biography information for Mr Robin Walker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767763/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767763/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2017-10-09","Immigration","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, what the Government's policy is on ensuring non-EU nationals who are partners of UK nationals and became resident in the UK under EU freedom of movement laws can continue to live in the UK after the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Ged Killen","Rutherglen and Hamilton West","Gerard Killen","106719"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767764","Department for Exiting the European Union ","false","2017-10-17","<p>We fully recognise the importance of the UK’s machinery sector. The Government’s objective remains to secure trade with Europe that is tariff-free and as frictionless as possible in all sectors, including in heavy machinery. We will pursue an ambitious and comprehensive free trade agreement with the EU to achieve this. This includes zero tariffs on trade in goods and minimising the regulatory and market access barriers for both goods and services.</p><p>We will need to build a bridge from our exit to our future partnership, to allow business time to adjust, and to allow new systems to be put in place. Therefore we are proposing a time-limited implementation period where we continue to have access to one another’s markets on current terms. We expect this to last for a period of around two years. We are pressing to agree this as early as possible, so as to provide certainty but will of course be subject to ongoing negotiations.</p><p> </p>","Worcester","Mr Robin Walker",,"2017-10-17T14:33:57.183Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767764/answer","Biography information for Mr Robin Walker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767764/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767764/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union ","Exiting the European Union ","2017-10-09","Manufacturing Industries: Equipment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, what steps he plans to take to mitigate the potential effect of the UK leaving the EU on UK machinery manufacturers who wish to continue to export to EU countries.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","106463"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767765","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-10-16","<p>The UK’s ambition is to work towards a comprehensive future agreement with the EU, which includes securing the freest and most frictionless trade possible in goods. The UK wants to ensure a smooth exit, which minimises disruption for businesses and consumers when goods are placed on the UK and EU market. With regards to third party conformity and certification procedures, the Government aims to provide maximum legal certainty and confidence to citizens, consumers and businesses.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-10-16T14:16:48.62Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767765/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767765/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767765/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-10-09","Certification Quality Marks","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, whether he plans to take steps to retain the appointment of UK notified bodies which provide third party certification for the CE marking of products sold within the EU.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","106464"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767766","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2017-10-17","<p>The Department for Exiting the European Union is responsible for overseeing negotiations to leave the EU and establishing the future relationship between the UK and EU. As such all staff in the Department are dedicated to planning or supporting the work on EU exit.</p>","Wycombe","Mr Steve Baker",,"2017-10-17T14:36:53.73Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767766/answer","Biography information for Mr Steve Baker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767766/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767766/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2017-10-09","Department for Exiting the European Union: Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, what estimate his Department has made of the proportion of the Civil Service workforce in his Department dedicated to planning for (a) the UK leaving the EU and (b) projects relating to the UK leaving the EU.","false","Biography information for Mr David Lammy","Tottenham","Mr David Lammy","106574"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767991","Department for International Trade","false","2017-10-12","<p>The primary way that the Government ensures responsible trade in defence equipment is through our system of export controls. All export licences are assessed on a case by case basis against the Consolidated EU and National Arms Export Licensing Criteria. The Consolidated Criteria provide a thorough risk assessment framework. A licence will not be issued if to do so would be inconsistent with the Consolidated Criteria.</p>","Wyre Forest","Mark Garnier",,"2017-10-12T15:57:46.46Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767991/answer","Biography information for Mark Garnier","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767991/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767991/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-10-09","Arms Trade","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, what steps he is taking to ensure that the UK conducts its arms trade in a responsible manner.","false","Biography information for Keith Vaz","Leicester East","Keith Vaz","901075"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/768858","Department for International Trade","false","2017-10-12","<p>I most recently visited Qatar on 5<sup>th</sup> October, where I met the Prime Minister and members of his cabinet to discuss Trade and Investment between the UK and Qatar. These discussions included follow-up to my meeting with the Finance Minister in June and also the Qatar-UK Business and Investment Forum in Birmingham earlier this year where Qatar pledged £5bn of investment into the UK over the next 5 years.</p>","North Somerset","Dr Liam Fox",,"2017-10-12T16:24:32.533Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/768858/answer","Biography information for Dr Liam Fox","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/768858/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/768858/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-10-09","Overseas Trade: Qatar","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, what recent discussions he has had with the Government of Qatar on future trade and investment between the UK and Qatar.","false","Biography information for Mr Ranil Jayawardena","North East Hampshire","Mr Ranil Jayawardena","901080"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/769121","Women and Equalities","false","2017-10-12","<p>Girls are just as likely to do well in science, technology, enginerring and mathematics (STEM) GCSEs as boys and the number of girls taking STEM A Levels since 2010 has increased by 20%, but there’s more to do.</p><p> </p><p>STEM careers have a 19% pay premium and we are spending over £12m per year on programmes to increase take up of physics, computing and maths A Levels; for example, the Stimulating Physics Network which provides specific support to address the low uptake of physics.</p><p> </p><p>Apprenticeships are also a crucial route into engineering and that’s why the National College for High Speed Rail will be delivering apprenticeships in the industry and focusing on getting more young women to apply.</p>","Guildford","Anne Milton",,"2017-10-12T16:46:14.43Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/769121/answer","Biography information for Anne Milton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/769121/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/769121/answer",,,,,"31","Women and Equalities","Women and Equalities","2017-10-09","Females: Science and Engineering","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for Women and Equalities, what steps the Government is taking to increase the number of women taking up careers in science and engineering.","false","Biography information for Thangam Debbonaire","Bristol West","Thangam Debbonaire","901068"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/769122","Women and Equalities","false","2017-10-12","<p>The UK Government’s record on equalities is one of the best in the world and we are determined this will remain so as, and after, we leave the EU.</p><p>We will ensure all the protections in the Equality Act 2010, including the public sector equality duty, continue to apply once we have left the EU. This will ensure women’s rights of protection against discrimination are preserved, and provide a strong platform for further progress</p>","Guildford","Anne Milton",,"2017-10-12T16:42:31.103Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/769122/answer","Biography information for Anne Milton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/769122/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/769122/answer",,,,,"31","Women and Equalities","Women and Equalities","2017-10-09","Feminism","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for Women and Equalities, what assessment she has made of the potential effect on women's rights of the UK leaving the EU.","false","Biography information for Stella Creasy","Walthamstow","Stella Creasy","901066"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/769123","Women and Equalities","false","2017-10-12","<p>The National LGBT Survey will be closing on 15 October. We have received over 100,000 responses. We will analyse and publish the results and use the evidence to inform government policy on LGBT equality.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2017-10-12T16:42:20.197Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/769123/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/769123/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/769123/answer",,,,,"31","Women and Equalities","Women and Equalities","2017-10-09","LGBT People: Public Sector","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for Women and Equalities, what progress the Government is making on its consultation with LGBT people on their experiences of accessing public services.","false","Biography information for Ged Killen","Rutherglen and Hamilton West","Gerard Killen","901069"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/769124","Women and Equalities","false","2017-10-12","<p>I was delighted that my Rt hon. Friend, the Chancellor of the Exchequer, announced a £5 million fund to celebrate the centenary of the Representation of the People Act, and I have written to all hon. Members outlining how constituents will access the fund. The hope is that the centenary will build a legacy by educating a new generation about the hard-won right to vote.</p>","Guildford","Anne Milton",,"2017-10-12T16:40:42.237Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/769124/answer","Biography information for Anne Milton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/769124/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/769124/answer",,,,,"31","Women and Equalities","Women and Equalities","2017-10-09","Females: Voting Rights","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for Women and Equalities, what steps the Government is taking to celebrate the centenary of women being able to vote.","false","Biography information for Chris Davies","Brecon and Radnorshire","Chris Davies","901064"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/769125","Department for International Trade","false","2017-10-12","<p>All ministers have observed a strong interest in British goods and services overseas. This is supported by the EEF, who said:</p><p>“Britain’s manufacturers are enjoying buoyant conditions on the back of export markets going from strength to strength.”</p><p>Latest trade figures also show that in the year to August 2017, UK exports have increased 13.1% on the previous 12 months.</p><p> </p>","North Somerset","Dr Liam Fox",,"2017-10-12T16:22:44.507Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/769125/answer","Biography information for Dr Liam Fox","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/769125/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/769125/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-10-09","Exports","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, what recent assessment he has made of trends in demand for UK exports.","false","Biography information for Matt Warman","Boston and Skegness","Matt Warman","901084"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/769126","Department for International Trade","false","2017-10-12","<p>The Government is developing a range of options for identifying and tackling non-tariff market access barriers once we leave the EU. The Secretary of State and I host regular Ministerial Trade Dialogues with overseas markets, which provide an excellent forum for addressing non-tariff barriers to trade. The Government will continue to deploy its international network, and is also able to conduct trade reviews to identify and address trade and investment barriers.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2017-10-12T15:46:53.443Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/769126/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/769126/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/769126/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-10-09","Overseas Trade and Foreign Investment in UK","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, what steps he is taking to identify potential barriers to trade and investment after the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Nigel Huddleston","Mid Worcestershire","Nigel Huddleston","901077"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/769127","Department for International Trade","false","2017-10-12","<p>Currently all UK trade with members of the WTO is subject to WTO rules. This will not change when the UK leaves the EU.</p><p>DIT will continue to contribute trade policy expertise to input into DExEU’s preparations and negotiations with the EU.</p><p>We want the UK to have the greatest possible tariff and barrier-free trade with our European neighbours and also to be able to negotiate our own trade agreements around the world.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2017-10-12T15:49:37.537Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/769127/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/769127/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/769127/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-10-09","UK Trade with EU","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, what assessment his Department has made of how World Trade Organisation rules would affect UK trade in the event that the UK leaves the EU without a trade deal.","false","Biography information for Wera Hobhouse","Bath","Wera Hobhouse","901078"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/769128","Department for International Trade","false","2017-10-12","<p>We are working with the US authorities to ensure the restrictions on British lamb are lifted as soon as possible. The US has a longstanding ban on the use of animal lungs as food, but the Scottish haggis industry is working on a US-specific recipe to allow the industry access to the US market at the earliest opportunity.</p>","Wyre Forest","Mark Garnier",,"2017-10-12T15:54:55.087Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/769128/answer","Biography information for Mark Garnier","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/769128/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/769128/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-10-09","Meat Products: USA","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, what representations he has made to his US counterpart on lifting the US ban on haggis imports.","false","Biography information for Stephen Kerr","Stirling","Stephen Kerr","901083"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/769129","Department for International Trade","false","2017-10-12","<p>I have raised the US anti-dumping and subsidies investigation into Bombardier personally with Trade Commissioner Malmström, just prior to the Department of Commerce’s preliminary determination of 26 September.</p>","North Somerset","Dr Liam Fox",,"2017-10-12T16:19:27.833Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/769129/answer","Biography information for Dr Liam Fox","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/769129/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/769129/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-10-09","Bombardier: USA","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, what discussions he has had with the EU Trade Commissioner on the Bombardier trade dispute.","false","Biography information for Martin Whitfield","East Lothian","Martin Whitfield","901079"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765156","Cabinet Office","false","2017-10-16","<p>All roles with access to sensitive information or systems are risk assessed. Staff and<br>contractors are vetted to the appropriate level to manage these risks.</p><p>Contractors working for Government departments are subject to the same security<br>standards and training as civil servants depending on their access to government systems<br>and information. Basic cyber security awareness is an essential protection against attacks<br>such as email phishing and departments are already providing training for their staff and<br>contractors on this.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-10-16T14:25:55.337Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765156/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765156/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765156/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-10-06","Government Departments: Cybercrime","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, pursuant to the Answer of 12 September 2017 to Question 7589, whether the Minister has made an assessment of differences in risk levels to cyber security between Civil Service staff and staff working for private firms contracted to do work by the Government.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","105431"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765157","Cabinet Office","false","2017-10-11","<p>The Government’s National Cyber Security Centre (NCSC) continues to develop an operational capacity to exchange cyber threat information at scale using open standards, beginning with organisations in the UK and the five eyes international partners, USA, Canada, Australia and New Zealand. Following an industry day earlier this year, NCSC is assessing a number of possible commercial product that would integrate into NCSC’s threat intelligence systems to ensure the effective delivery of this capability. It will deploy this in pilot during 2018 with a view to sharing it more widely thereafter.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-10-11T12:36:51Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765157/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765157/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765157/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-10-06","Cybercrime","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, pursuant to the Answer of 12 September 2017 to Question 7506, on cybercrime, who the international partners referred to in that Answer are and what the (a) number and (b) nature of the commercial offerings are for delivering this service.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","105432"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765158","Home Office","false","2017-10-16","<p>At the end of the 2016/2017 reporting period for Cyber Aware an estimated 11 million adults and 1.4 million SMEs nationally claimed they were maintaining or intending to take up key cyber security behaviours as a result of Cyber Aware.*</p><p> </p><p>This is based on evidence from the National Cyber Security Tracker, a regular online panel survey of approximately 4,000 consumers and 1,200 SMEs, designed to measure the adoption of safer cyber security behaviours.</p>","Wyre and Preston North","Mr Ben  Wallace",,"2017-10-16T14:48:31.913Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765158/answer","Biography information for Mr Ben Wallace","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765158/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765158/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-10-06","Cybercrime","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, pursuant to the Answer of 12 September 2017 to Question 7508, on cybercrime, what her estimate is of the size of the population who did not have any engagement with the CyberAware campaign.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","105433"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765159","Cabinet Office","false","2017-10-16","<p><strong>The Government Property Unit has held six formal governance meetings of the Property Leaders Board in the last twelve months. In addition ten bilateral meetings, covering the full range of GPU’s business with a department or departmental estates cluster, have been held since September 2016. One cluster now covers seven government departments. As stated in the response on 12 September 2017 there have also been a number of other formal meetings with departments on GPU programmes and the development of policy. These will have involved some heads of estates, but data on attendees by job role will have been captured in meeting minutes only and is not recorded in a central database.</strong></p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-10-16T09:57:48.393Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765159/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765159/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765159/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-10-06","Government Property Unit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, pursuant to the Answer of 12 September 2017 to Question 8211, on the Government Property Unit, how many formal meetings the unit had with each departmental head of estates in the last 12 months.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","105434"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765160","Cabinet Office","false","2017-11-14","<p>The Civil Service remains committed to becoming the most inclusive employer in the UK, these commitments are set out in the Civil Service Diversity &amp; Inclusion Strategy attached, and also available in the house library. The Strategy sets out how we will build on work delivered as part of the Talent Action Plan to improve the representation of under-represented groups and encourage inclusive behaviours. These priorities will be underpinned by a greater focus on accountability and assurance to deliver better outcomes for a diverse UK.</p><p>The Civil Service aims to be at the forefront of the diversity and inclusion agenda, leading the way in developing diverse and inclusive practices, policies and cultures. For example;</p><ul><li>To drive the changes in representation, each department will set targets on the flow of ethnic minority staff and disabled staff into their SCS.</li><li>A Diverse Leadership Task Force will be established to identify, recruit and develop people with Permanent Secretary potential from ethnic minority and disabled backgrounds.</li><li>The ground breaking Ethnicity Diversity Programme will enable greater innovation and the spread of best practice on increasing the representation of ethnic minorities within our talent pipelines.</li><li>The Disability Inclusion Programme will intensify efforts towards having a fair representation of disabled people at all levels but particularly the SCS.</li><li>Industry standard metrics for inclusion across the Civil Service and other employers across the UK will be established.</li><li>Inclusion will be seen as an essential leadership skill at senior levels in the Civil Service, but also as a basic core skill that all staff should demonstrate. Quality standards for inclusive leadership will be established and incorporated into the competency framework.</li></ul>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-11-14T11:37:49.843Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765160/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765160/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765160/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-10-06","Civil Servants: Recruitment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, pursuant to the Answer of 12 September 2017 to Question 7037, on Civil Service recruitment, what the other initiatives are which are hoped to bring positive impacts to the diversity of Civil Service recruitment.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","105437"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765161","Cabinet Office","false","2017-10-23","<p>The Civil Service Diversity &amp; Inclusion Strategy, published on the 16th October, sets out<br>how the Civil Service will approach becoming the most inclusive employer in the UK by<br>2020</p><p>We are committed to making anonymised recruitment the norm in the Civil Service, and<br>this approach sits within a wider suite of initiatives focussed on how this goal can be<br>achieved through innovative recruitment practices. Although, it is not possible to<br>disaggregate the impact of anonymised recruitments in isolation.</p><p>Alongside implementing the Civil Service Diversity &amp; Inclusion Strategy, we will publish<br>guidance and advice of the best evidenced interventions that can lead to a more diverse<br>and inclusive workforce. We will also measure the impact of improved recruitment<br>techniques and publish this data via an online Diversity Data Dashboard by April<br>2018.workforce. We will consider how we will measure the impact of improved recruitment<br>techniques within that work.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-10-23T14:49:54.717Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765161/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765161/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765161/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-10-06","Civil Servants: Recruitment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, pursuant to the Answer of 12 September 2017 to Question 7037, on Civil Service recruitment, what positive impacts can be measured thus far of the impact of anonymised recruitment.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","105438"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765162","Cabinet Office","false","2017-10-16","<p>The government does not hold figures on the breakdown of security training delivered to<br>staff and contractors centrally. Departments are responsible for ensuring their staff and<br>contractors are appropriately trained, subject to their role, business context and specific<br>risks</p><p>We recognise that targeted training to drastically reduce human error by staff and<br>contractors is crucial to delivering the National Cyber Security Strategy. We have<br>established a Government Security Profession to provide a consistent approach to cyber<br>security skills development across government.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-10-16T14:27:07.663Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765162/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765162/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765162/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-10-06","Government Departments: Cybercrime","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, pursuant to the Answer of 12 September 2017 to Question 7589, on cybercrime, how much is spent on this type of training for (a) staff and (b) contractors.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","105430"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765163","Cabinet Office","false","2017-10-12","<p>We are committed to improving and modernising electoral registration and are taking a<br>number of actions to meet this aim. For example, we are currently conducting 24 pilots<br>relating to the annual canvass with a view to simplifying this in future. The results of these<br>pilots will be available in 2018 and we will set out next steps at that time.</p><p>The programme is currently managing 23 local authorities undertaking canvass pilots this<br>year, following on from 3 local authorities who piloted last year. These pilots are the<br>starting point to gather evidence with the view of implementing changes to the canvass for<br>the 2019 canvass. The models that are currently being piloted look at how to reduce the<br>burdens of the canvass and reduce the bureaucracy. A working group with our key<br>stakeholders has been set up to start developing potential model ideas for a less<br>bureaucratic registration process.</p>","Kingswood","Chris Skidmore",,"2017-10-12T14:15:19.32Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765163/answer","Biography information for Chris Skidmore","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765163/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765163/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-10-06","Electoral Register","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what steps the Government plans to take to reduce bureaucracy in voter registration processes during and outside canvass periods.","false","Biography information for Cat Smith","Lancaster and Fleetwood","Cat Smith","105481"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765164","Cabinet Office","false","2017-10-16","<p>We do hold the names of organisations using the DNS filtering service. At this time<br>government is not publishing this information while we establish the DNS filtering service</p><p>We intend to publish this data internally within HMG at a future date to effect positive<br>behavioural changes across government. As of the end of September 2017, 73<br>government organisations are using this service.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-10-16T14:30:49.683Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765164/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765164/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765164/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-10-06","Government Departments: Cybercrime","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, pursuant to the Answer of 14 September 2017 to Question 7365, on Government departments: cybercrime, if he will list the 44 government organisations that are using DNS filtering.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","105506"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765165","Cabinet Office","true","2017-10-11","<p><del class="ministerial">Checking tax compliance is the responsibility of the contracting authority. This information is not held centrally. </del></p><p><ins class="ministerial">In the 12 months from 1 October 2016 to 30 September 2017, 59 users of the Mystery</ins><br /><ins class="ministerial">Shopper service waived their right to anonymity.</ins></p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-10-11T12:37:44.487Z","2017-10-12T14:09:19.673Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765165/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765165/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765165/answer","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765165/answer/previousversion/13716","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-10-06","Public Sector: Procurement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, pursuant to the Answer of 14 September 2017 to Question 7608, on Public Sector: Procurement, how many service users waived their right to anonymity in the last 12 months.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","105509"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765166","Cabinet Office","false","2017-10-12","<p><strong>The Government Property Unit currently has headcount of 76 FTE - of this only 2 staff are interims - this equates to 2.6% of our GPU headcount.</strong></p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-10-12T10:36:57.42Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765166/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765166/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765166/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-10-06","Government Property Unit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, pursuant to the Answer of 12 September 2017 to Question 8258, what proportion of the Government Property Unit's resource is (a) interim and (b) permanent.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","105510"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765167","Cabinet Office","false","2017-10-23","<p>GPU staff have an allocation of £964 per head for training in the current financial year. To<br>date, staff have used an average of £340 per head on training and development</p><p>Examples of the training undertaken include APM project management, and RICS training<br>courses.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-10-23T13:05:02.193Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765167/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765167/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765167/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-10-06","Government Property Unit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, pursuant to the Answer of 12 September 2017 to Question 8258, on the Government Property Unit, what the budget is for staff learning and development; and if he will provide details on what that budget has been used for to date.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","105511"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765168","Cabinet Office","false","2017-10-12","<p>The Government Property Unit sets out its objectives and milestones in its Business Plan which is monitored internally throughout the year.</p><p>During 2017/18 there are a number of initiatives which will be managed by the Unit including the co-creation of a refreshed Government Estate Strategy with departments; work to prepare for the launch of the Government Property Agency; an on-going focus on the release of public land and assets for housing and capital receipts; launching phase 6 of the One Public Estate initiative and supporting the government’s Industrial Strategy through potential relocations.</p><p> </p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-10-12T10:37:53.213Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765168/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765168/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765168/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-10-06","Government Property Unit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, pursuant to the Answer of 12 September 2017 to Question 8258, what the expected peaks are that the Government Property Unit will have to manage.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","105512"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765169","Cabinet Office","false","2017-10-12","<p>The Shadow Government Property Agency (GPA) is committed to our internal assurance and audit of the evidence to support conditions precedent for Go-Live.</p><p>When all conditions are satisfied, a public announcement will be made for the official launch of the GPA.</p><p> </p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-10-12T10:38:59.69Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765169/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765169/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765169/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-10-06","Government Departments: Buildings","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, pursuant to the Answer of 12 September 2017 to Question 8204, on the live trials of the New Property Model, what evidence informing the Go-Live decision will be made public.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","105513"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765170","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-10-16","<p>The cyber security of the UK, including the protection of our citizens and their data online, is a top priority for the Government. Since the Equifax incident, the National Cyber Security Centre (NCSC), the National Crime Agency, the Financial Conduct Authority and the Information Commissioner’s Office have worked together to protect British citizens who may have been affected by the data breach. The NCSC has published updated advice on its website, advising members of the public on password re-use, avoiding related phishing emails and fraudulent phone calls, as well as giving information of how to report a cyber incident to Action Fraud. In addition, as part of our five-year, £1.9 billion National Cyber Security Strategy, the Government is working to ensure all organisations are secure online and resilient against cyber threats.</p><p> </p><p>Under the existing Data Protection Act, organisations must ensure appropriate cyber security measures are in place to protect personal data. Our new data protection regime, introduced through the Data Protection Bill, will introduce new requirements for reporting data breaches and more stringent fines.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2017-10-16T16:08:38.57Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765170/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765170/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765170/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2017-10-06","Equifax","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, what steps the Government is taking to improve protection for people's private data and finances as a result of the Equifax data breach.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","105514"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765171","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-10-16","<p>We do not hold information on the number of meetings the Information Commissioner and her staff hold with credit rating agencies or other organisations. The Information Commissioner's Office do publish the minutes and papers of meetings on their website, which can be found at https://ico.org.uk/about-the-ico/our-information/minutes-and-papers/.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2017-10-16T08:48:54.147Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765171/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765171/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765171/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2017-10-06","Information Commissioner: Credit Reference Agencies","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, what information her Department holds on the number of meetings that have taken place between staff of the Information Commissioner's Office and credit rating agencies during the last two years.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","105516"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765172","Cabinet Office","false","2017-10-11","<p>In 2017, 1,481 people in Merseyside have applied for apprenticeships under the Civil Service apprenticeship scheme, known as Civil Service Fast Track. Fast Track is not aimed purely at young people as it as no upper age limit.</p><p>143 were successful and all apprentices took up offers.</p><p>15 served in their first preference of Merseyside. The remaining apprentices were offered other locations in the UK.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-10-11T12:20:41.107Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765172/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765172/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765172/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-10-06","Government Departments: Apprentices","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many young people in Merseyside have applied for apprenticeships under the civil service apprenticeship scheme; how many such applications were successful; how many such apprenticeships were taken up; and how many of those apprentices served in areas which they had denoted they wished to serve in.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","105568"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765173","Department for Education","false","2017-10-16","<p>The Government does not systematically collect such reports but the Equality and Human Rights Commission, the independent public body sponsored by the Government Equalities Office, is responsible for monitoring the effectiveness of equality and human rights legislation.</p><p> </p><p>The Commission’s report ‘How Fair is Britain?’ (2010) and follow up research report 74 (“Public authority commitment and action to eliminate targeted harassment and violence”) included data about unlawful harassment in the workplace.</p><p> </p><p>The Advisory, Conciliation and Arbitration Service provides advice on employment rights and workplace disputes. Its study, ‘Seeking better solutions: tackling bullying and ill-treatment in Britain's workplaces’ (2015) looked at the latest research on workplace bullying.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2017-10-16T16:38:07.103Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765173/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765173/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765173/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-10-06","Employment: Bullying","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, which Government Department is responsible for collecting reports of (a) anti-Semitic, (b) Islamophobic, (c) racist and (d) homophobic bullying in the work place.","false","Biography information for Andrew Percy","Brigg and Goole","Andrew Percy","105558"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765174","Cabinet Office","false","2017-10-19","<p>The information requested falls within the responsibility of the UK Statistics Authority. I<br>have asked the Authority to reply.</p>","Kingswood","Chris Skidmore",,"2017-10-19T11:15:36.507Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765174/answer","Biography information for Chris Skidmore","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765174/answer","PQ 105762 v.03 (1).pdf","UKSA response","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765174/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-10-06","New Businesses: Bolton","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what information the Government holds on the number of new businesses that were established in Bolton in the most recent year for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Sir David Crausby","Bolton North East","Sir David Crausby","105762"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765175","HM Treasury","false","2017-10-16","<p>HMRC’s Supervised Businesses Register is updated daily and includes details of businesses supervised by HMRC for anti-money laundering purposes. Management Information is collected at the end of each month. As of 30th September 2017 there were 27,060 businesses on the register.</p><p>HMRC does not intend to publish the information on the Supervised Business Register in an open data format. This is to prevent misuse of the data by third parties.</p><p> </p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride","105556","2017-10-16T16:15:51.367Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765175/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765175/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765175/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-10-06","Financial Services: Registration","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, when the Supervised Businesses Register was last updated; and how many firms are currently on that Register.","false","Biography information for Dame Margaret Hodge","Barking","Dame Margaret Hodge","105555"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765176","HM Treasury","false","2017-10-16","<p>HMRC’s Supervised Businesses Register is updated daily and includes details of businesses supervised by HMRC for anti-money laundering purposes. Management Information is collected at the end of each month. As of 30th September 2017 there were 27,060 businesses on the register.</p><p>HMRC does not intend to publish the information on the Supervised Business Register in an open data format. This is to prevent misuse of the data by third parties.</p><p> </p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride","105555","2017-10-16T16:15:51.417Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765176/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765176/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765176/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-10-06","Financial Services: Registration","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, whether information provided in the Supervised Businesses Register will be published in open data format.","false","Biography information for Dame Margaret Hodge","Barking","Dame Margaret Hodge","105556"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765177","HM Treasury","false","2017-10-16","<p>I set out the Government’s position on public sector pay in the House of Commons on 12 September 2017. A copy of this statement is available at: <a href="http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-statement/Commons/2017-09-12/HCWS127" target="_blank">http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-statement/Commons/2017-09-12/HCWS127</a>.</p>","South West Norfolk","Elizabeth Truss",,"2017-10-16T14:30:07.683Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765177/answer","Biography information for Elizabeth Truss","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765177/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765177/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-10-06","Public Sector: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, if he will remove the pay cap for public sector workers in (a) Hull West and Hessle and (b) England.","false","Biography information for Emma Hardy","Kingston upon Hull West and Hessle","Emma Hardy","105540"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765178","HM Treasury","false","2017-10-16","<p>This response relates to the experience of nurseries and other regulated childcare providers who have sought to sign up to receive Tax-Free Childcare payments. As of 9 October, over 50,000 childcare providers (49% of all regulated providers) had successfully signed-up for Tax-Free Childcare.</p><p>Childcare providers sign-up with the childcare service to receive Tax-Free Childcare payments. The majority of childcare providers have been able to sign-up with no issues, and since launch, 84% of childcare providers have reported that they were “very satisfied” or “satisfied” with the childcare provider sign up process.</p><p>A small number of parents and providers have experienced technical difficulties using this service. There are currently 160 providers with an issue, 0.3% of the total that have signed up to date. We are working to fix these as soon as possible and in many cases can do so in a matter of days.</p>","South West Norfolk","Elizabeth Truss","105542 ; 105543","2017-10-16T14:54:21.273Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765178/answer","Biography information for Elizabeth Truss","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765178/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765178/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-10-06","Nurseries: Registration","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many families have been affected by administrative errors in registering nurseries in the last six months.","false","Biography information for Daniel Zeichner","Cambridge","Daniel Zeichner","105541"
