"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765306","Home Office","false","2017-10-17","<p>Standards in policing must be maintained and transferrable across forces in England and Wales, and it is vital that all officers have access to training that equips them to deliver the high standard of service that the public expects.</p><p> </p><p>The Degree Apprenticeship entry route forms a key part of the Police Education Qualifications Framework (PEQF) being developed by the College of Policing and is an important element of further professionalising and raising standards in policing.</p><p> </p><p>Welsh forces pay the apprenticeship levy, and those funds are passed back to the Welsh Government through the agreement which the Welsh Government negotiated with HM Treasury.</p><p> </p><p>As Wales is already receiving its share of the levy, there is a clear choice to for Welsh Government on whether it supports Welsh police officers by funding their apprenticeships.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2017-10-17T16:13:50.6Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765306/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765306/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765306/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-10-06","Police: Wales","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what assessment she has made of the efficacy of the apprenticeship levy on funding police training in Wales.","false","Biography information for Liz Saville Roberts","Dwyfor Meirionnydd","Liz Saville Roberts","105684"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765307","Home Office","false","2018-01-11","<p>Border Force do not centrally collate rostering data since this is recorded and maintained at port level. There would be a disproportionate cost involved in collating this information from each individual port throughout the UK.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2018-01-11T17:34:37.593Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765307/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765307/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765307/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-10-06","Immigration Controls: Heathrow Airport","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, pursuant to the Answer of 18 September 2017 to Question 10312, how many UK Border Force officers were deployed in each month between August 2016 and August 2017.","false","Biography information for Mr Virendra Sharma","Ealing, Southall","Mr Virendra Sharma","105685"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765308","Home Office","false","2017-10-11","<p>The Recovery Champion will provide a national leadership role around key aspects of the recovery agenda that support sustained recovery, in partnership with Public Health England. This will include looking at the support provided to those in recovery by public employment services, housing services, criminal justice agencies and mental health services.</p><p>There are no plans to appoint a bespoke harm reduction champion.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2017-10-11T11:12:47.217Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765308/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765308/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765308/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-10-06","Drugs: Misuse","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, whether her Department plans to (a) include harm reduction within the remit of the Recovery Champion and (b) appoint a bespoke harm reduction champion as part of the Government's new drugs strategy.","false","Biography information for Mary Glindon","North Tyneside","Mary Glindon","105686"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765309","Home Office","false","2017-10-12","<p>The Home Office endorses the Employer Supported Policing (ESP) scheme and has been clear that by supporting staff to volunteer in policing, employers can help keep their communities safe and at the same time help their employees learn valuable skills.</p><p> </p><p>It is for individual employers to consider whether they are able to offer paid leave for employees to access special constable training and undertake special constable duties. The Home Office allows up to ten days a year of paid special leave for Home Office employees to carry out special constable duties or training.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd","105665","2017-10-12T09:36:51.637Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765309/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765309/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765309/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-10-06","Special Constables: Leave","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what assessment her Department has made of the effect of the lack of paid leave on the take-up of the Employer Supported Policing scheme.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","105664"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765310","Home Office","false","2017-10-12","<p>The Home Office endorses the Employer Supported Policing (ESP) scheme and has been clear that by supporting staff to volunteer in policing, employers can help keep their communities safe and at the same time help their employees learn valuable skills.</p><p> </p><p>It is for individual employers to consider whether they are able to offer paid leave for employees to access special constable training and undertake special constable duties. The Home Office allows up to ten days a year of paid special leave for Home Office employees to carry out special constable duties or training.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd","105664","2017-10-12T09:36:51.7Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765310/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765310/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765310/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-10-06","Special Constables: Leave","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, if her Department will take steps to introduce paid leave for special constables to access training through the Employer Supported Policing scheme.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","105665"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765311","Home Office","false","2017-10-18","<p>The Government recognises the valuable contribution migrants make to our society and we welcome those with the skills and expertise to make our country better still. But we must manage the process properly so that our immigration system serves the national interest.</p><p> </p><p>We have been clear that after the UK leaves the EU, free movement will end, but migration between the UK and the EU will continue and we are considering a number of options as to how this might work. We will be setting out initial proposals for our future immigration arrangements later in the year.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Government recognises that it is important that we understand the impacts on the different sectors of the economy and the labour market and want to ensure that decisions on the long-term system are based on evidence. On July 2017, we commissioned the independent Migration Advisory Committee (MAC) to advise on the economic and social impacts of the UK’s exit from the European Union and also on how the UK’s immigration system should be aligned with a modern industrial strategy- and they will be presenting their report in September 2018. The MAC has also issued a public call for evidence- where sectoral bodies including those in the science, academic and research sectors can formally make representations. This is open until 27 October 2017. Details can be found on the gov.uk website at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/consultations/call-for-evidence-and-briefing-note-eea-workers-in-the-uk-labour-market" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/consultations/call-for-evidence-and-briefing-note-eea-workers-in-the-uk-labour-market</a></p><p> </p><p>The Government will carefully consider any recommendations made to it by the MAC before finalising the details of the future immigration system for EU nationals.</p><p> </p><p>The Government also regularly engages with sectoral bodies – including those in the scientific and academic sectors ­- to ensure our immigration routes work effectively to enable businesses to access the talent they need. Their views do, and will continue to, inform our decisions on any changes to the system.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis","105594","2017-10-18T14:37:25.507Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765311/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765311/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765311/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-10-06","Universities: EU Nationals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, with reference to the Government's policy paper, Collaboration on Science and Innovation: A Future Partnership Paper, published on 6 September 2017, whether it is her policy to extend visa entitlement to the spouses and dependents of EU academics who can work in the UK after the UK has left the EU.","false","Biography information for Stephen Gethins","North East Fife","Stephen Gethins","105612"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765312","Home Office","false","2017-10-17","<p>The Dublin III Regulation is a long-standing mechanism between EU Member States to determine responsibility for examining asylum claims. It is not an application route for transfer to the UK. At present we do not publish data on cases covered by the Dublin Regulation. Eurostat, the EU’s statistics agency, regularly publishes Member State figures, which can be found at:</p><p> </p><p><a href="http://ec.europa.eu/eurostat/statistics-explained/index.php/Dublin_statistics_on_countries_responsible_for_asylum_application" target="_blank">http://ec.europa.eu/eurostat/statistics-explained/index.php/Dublin_statistics_on_countries_responsible_for_asylum_application</a></p><p> </p><p>The Government has committed to publishing regular updates on the number of unaccompanied asylum seeking children transferred to the UK from Europe, including those transferred under the Dublin III Regulation. This data will be published in the coming months.</p><p> </p><p>Under the Dublin III Regulation, the UK has two months from receiving a request from another participating Member State to accept or reject responsibility for processing the asylum claim. Within this two month period, the Home Office will undertake a number of mandatory checks, including security and a local authority assessment. Where possible, the Home Office will decide cases ahead of the two month deadline.</p><p> </p><p>Once a Dublin request has been accepted, the Regulation provides that the sending Member State has six months to enact the transfer. The Home Office works closely with EU Member State partners to enact transfers as soon as possible and ahead of the six month timeframe.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2017-10-17T15:43:21.773Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765312/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765312/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765312/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-10-06","Refugees: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many applications from unaccompanied children her Department is considering under the Dublin III Regulation.","false","Biography information for Luke Pollard","Plymouth, Sutton and Devonport","Luke Pollard","105617"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765313","Home Office","false","2017-10-12","<p>The Incident Recording System captures reasons for delay in commencing fire fighting actions, fire and rescue services are not asked about failure to locate an incident as a result of non-updated GPS navigation systems.</p><p> </p><p>It is the responsibility of each fire and rescue authority through its Integrated Risk Management Plan to allocate its resources appropriately to manage its operational response.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2017-10-12T09:47:56.657Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765313/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765313/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765313/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-10-06","Fire and Rescue Services: Standards","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, on how many occasions fire service response times have been extended as a result of new build housing developments not being included in GPS navigation systems in each of the last three years.","false","Biography information for Jenny Chapman","Darlington","Jenny Chapman","105547"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765314","Home Office","false","2017-10-18","<p>The Home Office does not collect this information centrally. It is the responsibility of each democratically accountable Police and Crime Commissioner with their Chief Constable to deploy resources appropriately to meet the needs of their local community.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2017-10-18T12:08:49.827Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765314/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765314/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765314/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-10-06","Police: Standards","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, on how many occasions the police response has been delayed as a result of new build housing developments not being included in GPS navigation systems in each of the last three years.","false","Biography information for Jenny Chapman","Darlington","Jenny Chapman","105548"
