Transport Authority.</p><p>** to be paid.</p><p>*** Under the terms of the new Northern franchise agreement all subsidies are now paid directly to the train operator</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2017-10-16T15:12:02.183Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765477/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765477/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765477/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-10-06","Public Transport: West Yorkshire","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what funding the West Yorkshire Combined Authority has received from the public purse for public transport provision in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","105739"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765478","Department of Health","false","2017-10-12","<p>The Department does not collect data on daily smoking levels, and has made no estimate of daily smoking rates on an annual basis going forward. The Tobacco Control Plan for England, published in July, set out the Government’s ambition to reduce adult smoking prevalence to 12% by 2022, and to achieve a smokefree generation (5% adult prevalence or less) in the longer-term.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine",,"2017-10-12T12:58:35.583Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765478/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765478/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765478/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-10-06","Smoking","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what estimate his Department has made of daily smoking levels in the UK each year for the next 15 years.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","106212"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765479","Department of Health","false","2017-10-12","<p>Snus is classed as an oral tobacco product. Snus was banned in the United Kingdom under The Tobacco for Oral Use (Safety) Regulations 1992, which implemented EU Directive 92/41. This ban has been confirmed by subsequent regulations, most recently by EU Tobacco Products Directive 14/40, which has been transposed into UK law. The Commission has set out the evidence underpinning the ban. The impact assessment for the 2014 Directive can be found at:</p><p><a href="https://ec.europa.eu/health/sites/health/files/tobacco/docs/com_2012_788_ia_en.pdf" target="_blank">https://ec.europa.eu/health/sites/health/files/tobacco/docs/com_2012_788_ia_en.pdf</a></p>","Winchester","Steve Brine",,"2017-10-12T13:08:06.417Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765479/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765479/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765479/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-10-06","Oral Tobacco","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, if he will publish the scientific evidence upon which the Government based its ban on snus.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","106405"
